<subSubSection pageId="25" pageNumber="26" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="25.[151,1436,763,969]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">
Adult flies of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Hendel" baseAuthorityYear="1933" box="[311,431,763,789]" class="Insecta" family="Sciomyzidae" genus="Colobaea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="limbata">
<emphasis box="[311,431,763,789]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">C. limbata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
appear rather similar to those of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Zetterstedt" baseAuthorityYear="1847" box="[809,955,763,789]" class="Insecta" family="Sciomyzidae" genus="Colobaea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pectoralis">
<emphasis box="[809,828,763,789]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">C</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[843,955,763,789]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">pectoralis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Lundbeck" baseAuthorityYear="1923" box="[1011,1143,763,789]" class="Insecta" family="Sciomyzidae" genus="Colobaea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="punctata">
<emphasis box="[1011,1030,763,789]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">C</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1045,1143,763,788]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">punctata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, from which they may be distinguished by the presence of two black spots below the notopleural suture; the apically narrowed basal flagellomere, which is 3X as long as the width at base; and the dark, infuscated crossveins. The 
<typeStatus box="[1189,1237,835,861]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">type</typeStatus>
specimens in the ZIN (
<specimenCount box="[218,251,871,897]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" type="female">1♀</specimenCount>
, 
<specimenCount box="[266,301,871,897]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" type="male">1♂</specimenCount>
) were collected at “Chiva” [Khiva], 
<collectingCountry box="[721,850,871,897]" name="Uzbekistan" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Uzbekistan</collectingCountry>
, on 21 April (
<bibRefCitation author="Hendel, F." box="[1008,1159,871,897]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" pagination="39 - 56" refId="ref44531" refString="Hendel, F. (1933) Neue acalyptratae Musciden aus der palearktischen Region. Deutsche entomologische Zeitschrift, 1933, 39 - 56. https: // doi. org / 10.1002 / mmnd. 48019330103" type="journal article" year="1933">Hendel 1933</bibRefCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Hendel" baseAuthorityYear="1933" box="[1180,1383,871,897]" class="Insecta" family="Sciomyzidae" genus="Colobaea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="limbata">
<emphasis box="[1180,1383,871,897]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Colobaea limbata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
also is known from four specimens (
<specimenCount box="[514,549,907,933]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" type="female">3♀</specimenCount>
, 
<specimenCount box="[562,597,907,933]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" type="male">1♂</specimenCount>
) collected 24, 27, and 
<date box="[858,1004,906,933]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" value="1965-07-28">28 July 1965</date>
at three localities in nearby 
<collectingCountry box="[1326,1436,907,933]" name="Tajikistan" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Tajikistan</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Elberg, K. J. &amp; Remm, H." box="[159,412,943,969]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" pagination="59 - 64" refId="ref43768" refString="Elberg, K. J. &amp; Remm, H. (1974) Uusi andmeid ovarkarblaste (Diptera, Sciomyzidae) levikust noukogude liidis. (Neue Angaben uber die Verbreitung der Sciomyzidae [Diptera] in der USSR). Acta Commentationes Universitatis Tartuensis, 327 (8), 59 - 64." type="journal article" year="1974">Elberg &amp; Remm 1974</bibRefCitation>
). Nothing is known about the biology or immature stages of this species.
</paragraph>
